---
import ServicePage from '../../components/ServicePage.astro';

const orgId = new URL('/#organization', Astro.site).href;
const schema = [
  {
    '@context': 'https://schema.org',
    '@type': 'Service',
    name: 'Tax Services for Entertainers',
    serviceType: 'Entertainment tax services',
    description:
      'Tax management for musicians and entertainers: filings, sales tax, non-resident withholding for states and foreign countries, quarterly planning, and long-term tax strategy.',
    provider: { '@id': orgId },
    areaServed: [
      { '@type': 'AdministrativeArea', name: 'Nashville Metropolitan Area' },
      { '@type': 'Country', name: 'United States' },
    ],
  },
];
---

<ServicePage
  title="Tax Services for Entertainers & Musicians | BriBiz"
  description="Tax filings, planning, and multi-state and international withholding for musicians and entertainers — from quarterlies to long-term strategy."
  breadcrumbName="Tax Services"
  heroTitle="Tax Services for Entertainers"
  schema={schema}
  related={[
    ['Business management', '/services/business-management/'],
    ['Tour accounting', '/services/tour-management/'],
    ['Royalty accounting', '/services/royalty-accounting/'],
  ]}
>
  <p>
    Too many artists meet their tax bill the hard way: a surprise five-figure
    number in April because nobody told them freelancers are supposed to set
    money aside all year. If you're self-employed – and as a working musician,
    you almost certainly are – taxes aren't a season. They're a system that runs
    all year, and somebody needs to be running it.
  </p>

  <h2>Income That Never Sits Still</h2>
  <p>
    A salary makes taxes simple. Music doesn't. You might make $30,000 one month
    and nothing the next, with royalties, show money, and session work all
    arriving on different schedules. We manage the system underneath: setting
    aside the right slice as money comes in, keeping your quarterly estimated
    payments on track, and making sure the payroll tax documentation for your
    business and crew is complete and up to date – so tax season is a checkpoint,
    not a panic.
  </p>

  <h2>Every State You Play, Every Country You Tour</h2>
  <p>
    Touring artists don't file like normal businesses. Play a show in another
    state and that state may want its cut; tour internationally and foreign
    withholding enters the picture. We manage filings, sales tax, and
    non-resident withholding taxes for states and foreign countries – the part of
    <a href="/services/tour-management/">touring</a> nobody puts on the poster.
    We've handled compliance and immigration paperwork issues for clients,
    keeping everything above board so there are no surprises down the road.
  </p>

  <h2>Planning, Not Just Filing</h2>
  <p>
    Filing what happened last year is the floor. The real value is in planning
    what happens next: structuring toward a better long-term tax situation,
    thinking through how your band or business entity is set up, and allocating
    money ahead of the bill instead of after it. And because we stay free agents
    rather than keeping one accountant in-house, we'll connect you with the right
    tax specialist for your situation – whether you're planning for retirement,
    accounting for global earnings, or running a nonprofit – and sit in those
    meetings with you.
  </p>
</ServicePage>
